      "step_index": 2,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "### 2) REASON (SAR) \u2014 why features affect CYP2D6 inhibition\nCYP2D6 inhibitors commonly present a **protonatable basic center** that can engage an acidic residue in the active site (often Asp301), plus **lipophilic/aromatic bulk** to occupy a hydrophobic pocket.",
      "tool_name": null,
      "tool_input": null,
      "tool_output": null,
      "timestamp": "2026-02-26T19:37:42.755236+00:00"
    },
    {
      "step_id": "9fb009a7",
      "step_index": 3,
      "step_type": "reasoning",
      "content": "- **Basic nitrogen:** present (primary amine), so *in principle* it can support binding.\n- **But polarity is very high:** **two carboxylates** strongly increase hydrophilicity and reduce the likelihood of tight binding in the predominantly hydrophobic CYP active site. Many potent CYP2D6 inhibitors are **cationic and lipophilic**, not zwitterionic/diacid.\n- **Aromatic content:** only **one phenyl ring** (moderate), and no additional lipophilic rings/heteroaromatics to strengthen binding.\n- **Overall size:** likely **MW ~200-ish**, within the typical range, but size alone doesn\u2019t compensate for unfavorable polarity/charge distribution.",
